free.chess
Class Position

java.lang.Object
  free.chess.Position

public class Position
extends java.lang.Object

Represents a position in one of the chess wild variants. The Position class itself is generally variant independent, but it does make some assumptions, such as the board being a 8x8 container of pieces, there being two players and other things common to most chess variants. IMPORTANT: This class is not thread safe.

setLexigraphic

public void setLexigraphic(java.lang.String pos)
Sets this Position to represent the position represented by the given string. The string should represent a position by specifying 64 characters indicating what occupies (-PNBRQKpnbrqk) each square, in lexigraphic order (a8, b8, ..., h1). The player to move will be the player with the white pieces.

Parameters:
pos - The string representing the position.
Throws:
PositionFormatException - if the given string is not in the expected format.

getLexigraphic

public java.lang.String getLexigraphic()
Returns a string representing the position by 64 characters indicating what occupies (obtained by calling toShortColorString() on each piece, '-' for no piece) each square, in lexigraphic order (a8, b8, ..., h1).

setFEN

public void setFEN(java.lang.String fen)
Sets this Position to represent the position described by the given string in FEN format. The FEN format is described at http://www.very-best.de/pgn-spec.htm#16.1. The characters describing pieces aren't limited to the chess set (like in FEN), but are determined by the WildVariant of this position.

Throws:
PositionFormatException - if the given string is not in the expected format.

getFEN

public java.lang.String getFEN()
Returns the FEN representation of this Position. May return null if the position wasn't set via the setFEN method.
